04122nam a22004815i 9780773589650DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735896507 a10.1515/97807735896502doi  a(DE-B1597)658072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBL432b.L48 2013eb 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a299/.94094772231 aLesiv, Mariya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Return of Ancestral Gods :bModern Ukrainian Paganism as an Alternative Vision for a Nation /cMariya Lesiv. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b20 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v26500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t“Living with Honour”: Modern Western Paganism -- t“Where Do They Get This From?” Sources of Ukrainian Paganism -- tUkrainian Pagan Groups History, Ideology, and Spirituality -- tBoundaries and Borders Cultural Context -- t“We Haven’t Given Up What Is Ours” Past and Present -- tGlory to Dazhboh (Sun-God) or to All Native Gods? Monotheism and Polytheism -- t“Where Else Is There Such a People?” Vision for a Nation -- t“We Allowed Nature to Live in Our Holy Place” Nature and Power -- t“This Is Indeed Ours!” Religious Syncretism -- tIn Spite of Politics Aesthetics and Beauty -- tConcluding Remarks Ukrainian Paganism in the Context of Modernity -- tTerms -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs Ukraine struggles to find its national identity, modern Ukrainian Pagans offer an alternative vision of the Ukrainian nation. Drawing inspiration from the spiritual life of past millennia, they strive to return to the pre-Christian roots of their ancestors. Since Christianity dominates the spiritual discourse in Ukraine, Pagans are marginalized, and their ideas are perceived as radical. In The Return of Ancestral Gods, Mariya Lesiv explores Pagan beliefs and practices in Ukraine and amongst the North American Ukrainian diaspora. Drawing on intensive fieldwork, archival documents, and published sources not available in English, she allows the voices of Pagans to be heard. Paganism in Slavic countries is heavily charged with ethno-nationalist politics, and previous scholarship has mainly focused on this aspect. Lesiv finds it important to consider not only how Paganism is preached but also the way that it is understood on a private level. She shows that many Ukrainians embrace Paganism because of its aesthetic aspects rather than its associated politics and discusses the role that aesthetics may play in the further development of Ukrainian Paganism. Paganism in Eastern Europe remains underrepresented within Pagan studies, and this work helps to fill that gap. Extensive comparative references to various forms of Western Paganism allows English-speaking readers to better understand the world of Ukrainian Pagans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNeopaganismzUkraine. 0aPaganismzUkraine. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358965040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773589650423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773589650/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles